What I never quite heard were :  

- Perfection is a lie (it made me learn Classes tho);

- "The best developers take breaks and have boundaries"

I find that if I start with the simplest thing and go from there, I work it out. When first playing with C, VBA, assembler, Python, Docker - "Hello World" showed that my software was installed properly, the configuration (if any) was good, and then I could start building up the little pieces that add up to a big piece.

Making sure the little piece works before going on. Writing 100 lines and having the compiler/interpreter crash means something's wrong somewhere. But where? If it isn't obvious with a quick review, then start over, going one step at a time, or save a copy and then start slicing out modular code. If you don't have modular code, even if the "modules" are noting but indented lines in one page of code, the reason it is bombing either has to be easy or you will waste time trying to chase the crazy squirrel that is having fun with your efforts. 

Writing modular code, short code, code with full names for variables, procedures and constants will save a LOT of time. If not now, then in the future. Trying to decipher: 

IF dm2 <> gth and ujsu < .982928 then  
   CALL dnkysu 
  if A1 <> B3 then
    z1++
  end if
 call SSUUSJW!!
S1(x1, hysh22)
D2(z, hsuj)
. . . . and on and on
END IF

Two busy weeks, moths, or years later and running through a lot of vague code will confuse you and make you rework the logic over. Not bad for simple logic, but when its a lot of code you do not need to be deciphering what "R1, R2, C2, d2, e, e1, fg etc" means.

Not when something like "videoRow1" or "targetSheet.cell(headerRow, SalesColumn)" etc. tells you what (or almost what) you were thinking at a glance.

